<TEXT>
the nations unemployment rate shot up to 55 
percent last month its highest level in two years the government 
said friday in a report that renewed fears that the economy may be 
toppling into a recession 
the economy appears to be caving in to a fullfledged 
recession the jump in the unemployment rate is the telling sign 
said allen sinai chief economist at the boston co 
on wall street the stock market sold off sharply amid the new 
recession fears and middle east oil concerns the dow jones average 
of 30 industrials down more than 120 points at its midsession low 
closed with a 5495point loss at 280965 
the labor departments unemployment report showed widespread 
weakness in the job market as payrolls fell by 219000 jobs 
that number was bloated by the 160000 temporary census workers 
the government laid off but other sectors of the economy posted 
job losses too construction and manufacturing continued their 
slide and even the nations service sector which had been carrying 
the economy suffered in july 
its one more nail in the coffin of the economic boom when 
you have 219000 people out there without jobs even if many of 
them were census workers youve got a lot of people without buying 
power its pretty clear evidence the economy is in big trouble 
said irwin kellner chief economist of manufacturers hanover trust 
the bush administration interpreted the numbers differently 
spokesman marlin fitzwater said the report does reinforce our 
concern for getting the deficit under control but said the 
economy is still growing we dont see a recession he said 
but richard rahn chief economist for the us chamber of 
commerce said the us economy is not going to hang on much 
longer it is headed directly into a recession 
analysts were also alarmed about how americas already 
struggling economy might react to oil price shock from iraqs 
invasion of kuwait 
were close to the edge it wouldnt take much of a breeze to 
push us over whats going on in the middle east may be the 
breeze to do it said robert dederick chief economist at the 
northern trust co of chicago 
fridays statistics were the latest in a string of lackluster 
government reports on economic activity that showed 
the us economy grew by just 12 percent in the second quarter 
of 1990 a rate far below the pace analysts believe is needed to 
generate new jobs 
orders to factories for manufactured goods fell in june for the 
third time this year a 15 percent decline which was likely to 
trigger further production cutbacks and layoffs in us industry 
construction spending was unchanged in june after falling for 
two consecutive months 
the governments index of leading economic indicators which 
has been flashing weak signals for most of the year showed no 
strength at all in june the index is designed to forecast economic 
activity six to nine months in advance 
last months 03 percentage point rise in the civilian jobless 
rate which was up from the june rate of 52 percent put the 
american unemployment rate at its highest level since it hit 56 
percent in august 1988 the labor department said 
analysts had been expecting the jobless rate to jump eventually 
to reflect the nations slow economic growth so far this year 
americas private industries have been producing an average of just 
96000 new jobs a month far below the 177000 generated monthly in 
1989 the labor department said 
janet norwood commissioner of the bureau of labor statistics 
blamed julys weak jobs report on the deterioration of the service 
sector that had been the major engine of job growth during the 
current economic expansion but that engine seems to have sputtered 
in july 
the service sector suffered a 160000jobs decline last month 
that number included temporary census workers as well as jobs in 
wholesale trade and business services retail trade added 20000 
jobs the government said 
construction payrolls fell by 50000 jobs after seasonal 
adjustment the fifth consecutive decline and a reflection of 
continued weakness in the housing market construction jobs are 
more than 100000 below the level of last fall the government said 
the nations manufacturing slump also continued in july as 
factory payrolls fell by 7000 jobs it was the 15th time in 16 
months that manufacturing jobs declined since reaching a 
postrecession peak in march 1989 nearly 350000 factory jobs have 
been lost 
health services which had added an average of 50000 jobs each 
month in the first half of this year expanded by only half that 
amount in july adding 25000 new jobs 
labor costs continued to increase average hourly earnings 
posted a 06 percent rise in july to 1009 up from the 1003 the 
average worker earned per hour in june 
overall total civilian employment was about 118 million in 
july down from the 1184 million employed in june the jobless 
numbered 68 million up from 64 million unemployed in june 
last months big jump in unemployment was a major departure from 
the steady nature of the jobless rate over the past two years 
before july the jobless rate had fluctuated within a tenth of a 
percentage point of 53 percent since september 1988 the only 
exception was march of last year when it hit a 15year low of 5 
percent 
</TEXT>
