<TEXT>
after years of collecting the remnants of 
yiddish literature which was virtually wiped out by the holocaust 
aaron lansky is taking the culture back to its roots 
lansky founder of the national yiddish book center recently 
returned from a mission of remembrance taking yiddish books to 
jews in the baltic republics of the soviet union 
these are jews that have been cut off from their own past 
lansky said friday unless they can connect now i think theyll 
simply lose it 
lansky and his associates packed up 6000 volumes in a rented 
van and drove for 12 days through the baltic states handing out 
copies of a written tradition that has nearly vanished in two 
generations 
he recalled in particular a trip to a town in lithuania that had 
been predominantly jewish before world war ii 
there was just no trace of jewish life at all lansky said 
had we been in that town 49 years before most of the people on 
the street would have been speaking yiddish to us here was a town 
that was virtually unchanged yet the jews had vanished 
lansky 35 began rescuing yiddish 10 years ago when he 
founded the national yiddish book center in western massachusetts 
running newspaper ads for unwanted yiddish books languishing in 
attics and cellars at that time it was estimated that 75000 
books existed written in the language that had been spoken by 
eastern european jews for hundreds of years 
instead about a million books have poured into the nonprofit 
center the largest repository of yiddish works in the nation 
which now has a staff of about two dozen and runs such educational 
programs as the yiddish library development program 
lansky got the idea to take books into the soviet union after 
receiving letters from jews in the baltic states who had heard of 
the center and hoped that the new openness would mean yiddish could 
be resuscitated 
the books were sent to finland and then to estonia where a 
nonjewish group the estonia cultural foundation had agreed to 
accept them lansky an associate and a photographer flew to 
stockholm rented a van and then drove to estonia 
we were there exactly 50 years to the day of the soviet 
occupation of the baltic states so it was an historic time 
lansky said 
many of the books in the van were reprints of works that had 
been originally published in the baltic states during the 100 or so 
years that yiddish literature flourished starting about 1870 
lansky said although many of the jews he spoke to hope to leave 
the soviet union now that immigration has relaxed somewhat they 
still want to keep in touch with their old traditions 
their grandparents were yiddishspeaking jews theyre not 
russians theyre not latvians it says right in the passport that 
theyre a jew but they havent the slightest idea what that 
means he said 
</TEXT>
