<DOCNO> AP900804-0007 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the next president of colombia is a 
softspoken economist who was catapulted to his nations highest 
office less through charisma than by violent events 
cesar gaviria of the liberal party the former campaign manager 
for a candidate who was killed by drug traffickers will become 
colombias next leader on tuesday 
he is a small man with a thin voice and a childlike face but as 
a congressman and cabinet minister he gained a reputation for 
being a tough negotiator and political manipulator 
hes a 21stcentury type smart practical and pragmatic 
said jorge orlando melo director of bogotas institute of 
political studies 
one year ago gaviria was campaign manager for sen luis carlos 
galan an antidrug crusader who was slain at a rally by drug 
traffickers 
galans death signified the start of a bloody war against drug 
lords it also marked the political rise of gaviria who vowed to 
carry on galans crusade against drug criminals who were 
endangering colombian democracy 
in many ways colombians were voting for a dead man when they 
chose gaviria said political scientist camilo castellanos 
colombians devastated by a seemingly endless nightmare of 
bombings and murders now look to gaviria to defend their countrys 
dignity 
he takes office at a time when drug lords have declared a 
ceasefire several leftist guerrilla groups are talking peace with 
the government and political leaders have agreed to call a national 
assembly to reform colombias 104yearold constitution 
but the atmosphere of hope is muted by the continued violence 
assassinations of political leaders judges and policemen 
continue guerrillas still fight the army in the countryside 
earlier this week police said they thwarted a plan by 
terrorists to disrupt next weeks inaugural ceremonies security 
forces found three uzi machine guns that they said were to be used 
to carry out terrorist attacks during the inauguration 
officials say tough security measures will protect the five 
heads of state and 81 foreign delegations visiting colombia for the 
inauguration 
but recent terrorist attacks underscore the fact that no one is 
truly safe in colombia as long as so many violent elements run free 
gaviria has promised to continue the tough stance against drug 
traffickers taken by the current administration of president 
virgilio barco 
observers say that one of barcos greatest achievements as 
president was getting the world to admit that the drug war was not 
just colombias problem 
during barcos tenure colombia went from being the criminal 
to the victim in the worlds eyes melo said 
but if barcos biggest feat was getting the world to admit the 
problem gavirias biggest challenge is getting it to act 
critics charge that barcos diplomatic successes were not 
supported by enough foreign aid to help colombia fight the drug war 
last year the united states sent 65 million in logistical aid 
such as helicopters and bulletproof vests 
however the economic assistance colombia had hoped for such as 
preferential treatment for its exports never materialized 
compared to barco gaviria is going to insist much more on the 
economic part getting commercial aid international credits 
etc melo said 
some observers say gaviria represents a new breed of colombian 
political leaders who shun the closed oldboy network of the past 
he has promised to open up the political system to 
underrepresented groups 
but not everyone agrees gaviria represents a change 
in order for anyone to get to where gaviria is youd have to 
play by the rules and those rules arent available to everyone 
human rights activist clara lopez said in an interview 
</TEXT>
