<DOCNO> AP900804-0009 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
us air force jets have screamed low over western 
canyonlands for years practicing bombing runs for a potential war 
against the soviet union in the volatile middle east 
now the persian gulf is aflame with gunfire but the 
superpowers are on the same side trying to halt the violence from 
day one 
fridays historic joint statement condemning iraq made in 
moscow by us secretary of state james a baker iii and soviet 
foreign minister eduard shevardnadze is the first time the 
superpowers coordinated specific sanctions to stop a war 
they condemned the brutal and illegal invasion of kuwait by 
iraqi military forces and agreed to seek a worldwide cutoff of 
arms shipments to the aggressor they asked the entire 
international community to join in taking all possible steps to 
restore kuwaits independence 
these steps that we have outlined are a lot more than simply 
rhetoric these are specific and concrete actions baker told a 
news conference 
the soviet union iraqs largest weapons supplier had already 
announced it was suspending arms shipments because of the invasion 
the united states which sells no military equipment to iraq froze 
iraqs bank accounts and banned imports of its oil 
the superpowers have cooperated in the past in the united 
nations on such fruitless endeavors as seeking peace for lebanon 
but fridays action is the first time they have tried to strangle a 
war by cutting off the aggressors resources 
it was a stark example of the radical change in soviet foreign 
policy over five years of mikhail s gorbachevs rule he has been 
saying for years that conflicts must be decided peacefully but the 
arms embargo backed words with action at the cost of angering a 
longtime ally 
fridays meeting also brought dramatic evidence that the cold 
war is truly over this time there is no fear that someone elses 
temper would turn an icy superpower confrontation into a 
conflagration that could destroy the earth 
iraqi soldiers overran kuwait and on friday gathered on the 
border with saudi arabia in spite of a clear warning that the 
united states may enter the war if saudi arabia is attacked 
for years the united states feared that a threat to saudi arabia 
would lead directly to a war between the superpowers but 
shevardnadze made it clear the soviet union has no intention of 
sending its own troops to the persian gulf 
there are no such plans he said 
shevardnadze also said he still believes iraq will have the 
political wisdom to end its occupation of kuwait 
he said one day after the soviet union cut off arms to iraq 
that baghdad had assured soviet diplomats its troops would begin 
withdrawing soon 
shevardnadze also warned of very very severe consequences 
if any of the thousands of soviet citizens in kuwait and iraq are 
hurt 
shortly after shevardnadzes announcement baghdad radio said 
iraqi troops would begin leaving sunday because the provisional 
government set up during the invasion could stand on its own 
western diplomats called the new kuwaiti government a puppet regime 
under the control of iraqi leader saddam hussein 
shevardnadze admitted that when he and baker meeting in 
irkutsk on wednesday first discussed the iraqi troops massing on 
the kuwaiti border i did not expect the iraqis would resort to 
such an overt invasion an undistinguished aggression against a 
defenseless peaceloving country which did not and does not 
threaten anyone 
shevardnadze said that if iraq does not withdraw the 
superpowers would continue to work together to that end and the 
soviet union would consider further steps of its own beyond the 
arms embargo 
president bush said the united states might blockade iraqs 
oilshipping routes 
richard grimmett of the us congressional research service said 
a worldwide arms cutoff would have no immediate effect on iraq 
because it has imported 43 billion worth of weapons in the past 
eight years 
but if the soviets the french the germans and the british all 
refused to sell arms to iraq and kept up the embargo for four or 
five years there is nobody out there who could take their place 
except possibly china that would eventually force saddam to stop 
his military aggression grimmett said 
bush hailed the transformation in americansoviet relations that 
allowed fridays events 
all the issues are on the table we dont dodge the tough 
ones and thats been the secret to our success so far bush told 
reporters in aspen colo on thursday 
a commentator for the novosti news agency vladimir alexeyev 
said friday that the sudden danger of war in the persian gulf just 
as european tensions are disappearing shows world peace is like a 
patchwork quilt as soon as a tear is mended in one place 
another appears somewhere else he wrote 
under these circumstances what is need are concentrated 
efforts on the part of all nations on all continents to work out 
a codex of international behavior that would effectively preclude 
the possibility of new local wars and local armed conflicts which 
pose a threat to peace and have the potential of turning into major 
conflagrations 
alexeyev said the bakershevardnadze meeting marked a new phase 
in superpower relations where egocentric ambitions are being set 
aside and the two nations are beginning to work together for the 
benefit of all mankind 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
ann imse based in moscow has been covering the 
soviet union for the associated press for two years 
</TEXT>
