<TEXT>
the house early saturday gave final 
congressional approval to legislation making permanent the 
dutyfree status on imports from 24 caribbean and central american 
nations including nicaragua and panama 
by a voice vote the house passed a trade bill extending 
permanently the dutyfree status of 4 billion a year in imports 
under former president reagans 1983 caribbean basin initiative 
but the house refused to expand it to cover imports of textiles 
shoes sugar and ethanol that might threaten us farmers and jobs 
the senate approved the bill earlier this week after lawmakers 
had spent nearly two months hammering out differences between its 
and the houses version the bill now goes to the white house for 
president bushs signature 
in addition to the cbi the bill also makes permanent what had 
been a yeartoyear ban on the export of raw logs from federal land 
and also from state lands in california oregon and alaska exports 
from stateowned land in washington would be reduced but not halted 
the log measure is intended to preserve the pacific northwests 
dwindling timber supply for domestic mills along with enough 
oldgrowth stands to save the northern spotted owl from extinction 
exports of logs from privately owned lands would still be 
allowed but the timber industry generally would be prohibited from 
substituting them for logs from federal lands as a way to escape 
the ban 
the caribbean basin initiative was intended to lift the regions 
depressed economy through a combination of direct aid and an 
elimination of tariffs and other trade barriers to encourage the 
development of exportoriented businesses 
excluded from dutyfree importation however were textiles 
clothing dinnerware luggage shoes and other sensitive goods 
that compete with usmade products import quotas also were kept 
on sugar 
critics say the initiative has failed to large degree because 
the direct governmenttogovernment aid fell victim to us budget 
deficits and drastically reduced imports of oil petroleum products 
and sugar from the region 
in 1983 when the initiative began caribbean and central 
american exports to the united states totaled nearly 88 billion 
by 1988 they had dropped to 6 billion to protect domestic sugar 
growers for example annual import quotas have been reduced from 
32 million tons to 12 million over the past seven years 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900804-0018 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
education secretary lauro f cavazos with the 
academic year approaching is quickening efforts to make sure banks 
continue to grant student loans 
cavazos said friday a deal will be announced within a few weeks 
to cover the defaulted loans guaranteed by the financially troubled 
higher education assistance foundation or heaf of overland park 
kan one of the nations largest insurers of those loans 
we are intensively involved in sensitive discussions with 
other organizations that have an interest in and capacity for 
assuming all of heafs guarantee functions cavazos told the 
senate labor and human resources education subcommittee 
we are committed to putting in place a solution that will 
ensure that new loans are made and insured without interruption 
and that the existing heaf portfolio is properly serviced 
collected insured and reinsured he said 
he told the panel the arrangement would be in place within a 
few weeks 
education department spokeswoman etta fielek said it is unlikely 
heaf will survive the restructuring 
the financially threatened foundation guarantees student loans 
in minnesota west virginia kansas nebraska wyoming and the 
district of columbia and insures loans in other states as well 
heaf one of 47 guarantors nationwide told the education 
department four weeks ago it was having serious financial problems 
because of a high default rate 
the foundation blamed the problem on overlending to students who 
attend private trade and technical schools students from largely 
lowincome backgrounds who either drop out or earn too little after 
graduation to repay the loans 
cavazos who has already tightened regulations on loans for 
students at private trade schools said he will seek further 
restrictions on their accreditation and licensing next year 
he also said regulations will be published next week aimed at 
barring false information from the schools 
under the student loan program banks make the student loans and 
groups such as heaf guarantee that they will be repaid and take 
over collection the federal student loan marketing association 
known as sallie mae provides money to lenders by selling packages 
of loans to investors 
the education department is the backup insurer to the 
guarantors the taxpayers must make up the difference between the 
default liability and what the department takes in through loan 
fees and collections 
the department said last week that the taxpayer costs for the 
troubled foundation would not surpass 100 million 
several alternatives have been suggested for the bailout a 
takeover by sallie mae a takeover by indianapolisbased united 
student aid funds another large guarantor and a spreading out of 
the bad loans over a number of agencies 
</TEXT>
