college students may be ordered to help bring in a 
bumper soviet harvest and delay the opening of their fall terms by 
one month according to vladilen nikitin director of the state 
food commission 
nikitin said prime minister nikolai ryzhkov signed an order 
friday drafting at least 15 percent of the nations civilian trucks 
to help with the harvest 
the officials tass news agency reported thursday that tens of 
thousands of soldiers and even kgb personnel are harvesting a grain 
crop estimated at a record 260 million tons 
we have to consider it reasonable to draft students for a 
month to permit deans to postpone studies for a month nikitin 
told the vremya tv news program friday 
the soviets are already losing 2 million tons a day because they 
cannot harvest and store the grain fast enough soviet news media 
blamed shortages of fuel trucks and storage space as well as the 
centrally planned economys inability to adjust to the demand 
