the senate early saturday voted to let the 
government sink 72 billion deeper into debt over the next two 
months a cash infusion designed to avert an unprecedented federal 
default 
the senate passed the bill by voice vote after the house on 
friday cleared the bill by a vote of 247172 
the bill requested by president bush would provide enough 
money to keep federal coffers full through oct 2 
last tuesday the house approved a longerterm extension of the 
debt limit providing 322 billion in borrowing authority but that 
measure the target of possible amendments in the senate is not 
expected to move toward enactment until after congress august 
recess 
the treasury has warned that the government will run out of 
money by aug 15 unless its authority to borrow money is extended 
with congress poised to begin its monthlong august recess at the 
close of business friday lawmakers had to approve the measure 
before leaving the capital 
by aug 15 the government is expected to deplete its 
cashonhand in doing so the total federal debt will hit a record 
312 trillion 
the government has never defaulted on its payments if it did 
so economists say interest rates would skyrocket and financial 
markets could be badly shaken 
failure to enact the bill would result in disastrous economic 
political and financial consequences said house ways and means 
committee chairman dan rostenkowski dill 
because debt limit extensions are mustpass legislation they 
consistently attract unrelated amendments that would have little 
chance of passage on their own 
oct 2 is the second day of fiscal 1991 
it is a date by which bush administration and congressional 
budget negotiators would like to complete their work on a 
deficitreduction deal 
because any budgetcutting pact would contain unpopular tax 
increases and spending cuts budget bargainers would like to attach 
their package to the next extension of the debt limit 
