senate and house negotiators on clean air 
legislation reached agreement on a schedule for ending by the 
close of the decade use of chemicals that damage the ozone layer 
but leaders acknowledged friday the most difficult issues of the 
legislation have yet to be discussed 
among other provisions the negotiators agreed to forbid states 
and local governments from restricting or banning the chemicals for 
two years 
the conference committee is not scheduled to meet again until 
after the august congressional recess house and senate staffers 
were directed to work through the month to draft possible 
compromises on various parts of the two bills 
negotiators said they hoped the agreement on ozonedestroying 
chemicals would help break the deadlock 
that agreement calls for phasing out such chemicals including 
chlorofluorocarbons halons and carbon tetrachloride widely used 
as coolants solvents and foam blowing agents by the end of the 
decade 
some substitute chemicals that are less harmful to the 
environment such as hcfcs chlorofluorocarbons that contain one or 
more hydrogen atoms would be phased out over the next 40 years 
the measure also calls for recylcing of these chemicals by 1992 
and the installation of precautions to prevent routine release into 
the air 
