the house passed and sent to president bush 
early today a bill triggered by the wreck of the exxon valdez that 
would strengthen federal oil spill liability laws 
the house approved 3600 the compromise worked out by a 
housesenate conference committee as one of its last actions before 
recessing for the summer it passed despite strong objections by 
some lawmakers to a oneyear moratorium on drilling off the north 
carolina coast 
the senate voted 990 thursday to approve the legislation more 
than 16 months after the exxon valdez tanker ran aground in prince 
william sound dumping 11 million gallons of crude oil into the 
pristine alaska waterway 
the oil spill bill says safe transportation of oil is going to 
be part of the cost of doing business said rep george miller 
dcalif the chairman of the house interior subcommittee on 
offshore energy resources 
he called the bill the first environmental salvo of the 
decade 
its not as strong as many of us would like to see it but 
its landmark legislation said rep gerry studds dmass 
chairman of the house merchant marine and fisheries subcommittee on 
the environment 
stephen hart deputy press secretary at the white house said 
bush has some reservations about the bill but no veto 
recommendations 
we have reservations because the protocols are not in the 
bill and that the conference added the moratorium on north 
carolina said hart 
the protocols are a reference to an international treaty not 
yet ratified by the united states that would lessen liability the 
bill puts a oneyear moratorium on drilling off the coast of north 
carolina until a study of possible effects can be completed 
miller and other lawmakers pushing for tougher liability laws 
said they hoped to pin more responsibility for spills on oil 
companies instead of just the shippers 
miller was satisfied however that companies using 
irresponsible shippers would eventually have to pay said a miller 
aide 
the bill also allows states to enact tougher laws 
lawmakers who have been trying for years to get a federal 
liability bill through congress consider the legislation a major 
breakthrough that seemed to need a tragedy as devastating as the 
march 24 1989 oil spill to become reality 
many of us are glad not to have to work on it again in another 
congress said studds whose efforts to strengthen oil spill laws 
go back to 1975 
the exxon valdez spill the worst in us history prompted 
demands for tougher federal requirements following the spill the 
house and senate each passed differing bills that took lengthy 
conference negotiations to reconcile 
major provisions in the legislation going to bush include 
liability by shippers for up to 1200 per gross ton of the 
tanker instead of the current ceiling of 150 per gross ton 
creation of a 1 billion oil spill response and cleanup fund 
with the money coming from a 5centabarrel fee on domestic and 
imported oil 
a requirement that all new tankers have double hulls and that 
most of the existing tankers be retrofitted with double hulls or 
taken out of service over the next 20 years a small number of 
tankers will be given until 2015 to have double hulls 
formation of regional response teams within the coast guard to 
deal with oil spills and a national response center where computers 
will hold lists of personnel and equipment that can be called upon 
after a major spill 
increased research on oil pollution control 
a requirement that the government check driving records for 
alcoholrelated offenses before issuing licenses to operate an oil 
tanker 
