county 
us district judge david v kenyon ruling in a historic voting 
rights lawsuit friday supported a redistricting plan that creates 
a hispanic majority district for the board of supervisors the 
countys top elected officials 
for the first time the hispanic community is going to be a 
meaningful part of the electorate in los angeles county said 
attorney mark rosenbaum who represented the american civil 
liberties union in the suit this means we can take down the 
hispanic need not apply sign 
kenyon ruled june 4 that the board of supervisors discriminated 
against hispanics when redrawing district boundaries after the 1980 
census kenyon found the supervisors violated the federal voting 
rights act and ordered the board to submit a new plan that would 
help a hispanic win a seat 
an estimated 35 percent of the countys 87 million residents 
are hispanic but the board has not had an elected hispanic member 
in 115 years 
jose roberto juarez an attorney for the mexican american legal 
defense and educational fund said kenyons decision sends a strong 
signal nationally to governments that will be redrawing voting 
boundaries on the basis of the 1990 census results 
the most important outcome of this lawsuit is the recognition 
that we are prepared to do battle for voting rights regardless of 
the size of the opponent he said 
under the new plan a supervisorial district held by a retiring 
conservative supervisor would be redrawn to give it a hispanic 
majority the other four districts would undergo minor adjustments 
that generally preserve voter bases of two liberal and two 
conservative supervisors 
kenyons ruling came in the form of a request to the plaintiffs 
to draw a plan to his liking the plaintiffs plans already 
submitted generally conform to what the judge has asked for 
kenyon still must issue a formal order to implement the new plan 
the ruling could change a decadelong 32 conservative majority 
with possible sweeping effects on such matters as health and social 
services funding 
