<TEXT>
increased ultraviolet light streaming 
through the earths depleted atmospheric ozone layer may be causing 
the mysterious deaths of toads frogs and other amphibians reported 
in widely scattered areas of the world an oregon state university 
zoologist said 
cautioning that evidence remains circumstantial andrew 
blaustein said friday that ultraviolet radiation could explain the 
recent mass dieoffs in two cascade range lakes in oregon and 
other declines in amphibian populations in the western united 
states costa rica and australia 
he said tadpoles taken from the stricken oregon lakes before the 
dieoffs and reared away from direct sunlight in his laboratory 
developed normally prompting the theory that uv light was to blame 
if this is the problem humans will be directly affected 
blaustein said in a telephone interview they will also be 
greatly indirectly affected if it is starting to kill animal life 
amphibians are not the only ones to go 
blaustein a professor of biology at the university in 
corvallis said the theory would be one of the main topics tuesday 
at a meeting in new orleans of scientists studying the recent 
declines in amphibian populations around the world 
i am getting somewhat alarmed blaustein said adding that 
many possible causes for the mass deaths had been ruled out i 
would say people studying amphibians are somewhat alarmed by the 
possibility it could be increased uv 
scientists have blamed releases of chlorofluorocarbon gases 
used as a coolant in refrigerators and air conditioners and as a 
propellant in aerosol cans for widespread thinning of the ozone 
layer which screens ultraviolet light from the sun 
in the spring blaustein and other scientists discovered all the 
western toad eggs had died in lost lake near santiam pass in the 
cascade range and all the frog tadpoles had disappeared from an 
unnamed lake nearby 
blaustein said research done at oregon state university in 1975 
by robert worrest showed toad eggs and tadpoles were very 
susceptible to increases in midrange ultraviolet radiation 
jack hardy associate professor of environmental studies at 
western washington university in bellingham has found increased 
ultraviolet light reduced ocean planktons ability to perform 
photosynthesis the vital oxygen producingprocess of plants 
socalled middle range ultraviolet light between 290 nanometers 
and 420 nanometers reduces photosynthesis causes genetic damage 
and skin cancer and could affect the growth of food crops and 
forests hardy said 
i would not be surprised if it affects frog egg hatches 
hardy said 
research in antarctica indicates that ultraviolet light is 
strongest in the springtime when amphibians would be in their 
larval stage and most susceptible to damage from sunlight he added 
in the northwest scientists have noted the western spotted frog 
is no longer found in western oregon and western washington and 
breeding populations of the redlegged frog have disappeared from 
oregons willamette valley blaustein said 
up to 40 species of amphibians in costa rica are now endangered 
and the golden toad has disappeared from a national park there 
the redlegged frog once the most common frog in california 
has disappeared from the central valley and is declining elsewhere 
the gastricbrooding frog can no longer be found in australia 
