ashore with praise for their soviet rescuers and acceptance of the 
oceans fury 
rolando arellano an apprentice officer from manila 
philippines said friday he would resume his oceangoing life and 
vowed not to give in to fear no this is life at sea 
arellano said 
twentyone survivors of the wrecked freighter corazon were 
brought ashore by a soviet fishing support ship that plucked them 
from churning seas in the atlantic about 400 miles east of new york 
six crew members including most of the ships officers died in 
the wreck tuesday 
what made the whole operation complicated was the wind and the 
height of the waves as well as the rainstorms very little 
visibility said capt vladimir pushnoy skipper of the soviet 
ship mv leonid leonidov speaking through an interpreter at a news 
conference 
one man spent about 10 hours in the water before he was hauled 
to safety pushnoy said 
the survivors were mostly greek or filipino sailors aboard the 
593foot freighter hauling tons of cement from greece to new york 
we are very lucky said ships cook pantelis potiris of 
athens greece it was very bad very rough 
arellano said he spent about five hours floating in the water 
after his life raft capsized 
i hope only to stay alive arellano said i always pray to 
god we are thinking of our family and to save ourselves 
many survivors had only life jackets for flotation and the 
yellow vests were hard to see amid the foam and spray of the rough 
water pushnoy said 
after the corazon sent a distress signal tuesday afternoon the 
us and canadian coast guards provided information to help the 
leonid leonidov and several other ships find the survivors 
two other ships in the area got close to corazon crew members 
but couldnt get them aboard 
pushnoy said his ship was able to pull off the rescue because 
his 46member crew is used to working on the open sea and tying up 
with other vessels under adverse conditions 
survivors from the corazon hugged their rescuers after the rusty 
soviet ship pulled into port 
the russians are good said one survivor giving a thumbsup 
