measure abandons the balance in the program 
but shelby said during the debate that the amendment would 
give the administration clear guidance on the sdi program 
we would be rejecting early deployment of systems that would 
violate the antiballistic missile treaty in favor of a continued 
research program on treatycompliant shortterm options and 
longerterm more effective defenses bingaman said recently 
under the provision the fiscal 1991 budget request for the 
phase 1 program would be cut from 19 billion to 15 billion in 
addition the measure would reduce the proposal for brilliant 
pebbles from 329 million to 129 million 
the amendment comes on the heels of a congressional report that 
found deploying the first phase of sdi in 1993 would be premature 
and fraught with high risk 
the general accounting office the investigative arm of 
congress said in the study that the introduction of the brilliant 
pebbles has drastically changed the sdi systems design leaving it 
in a state of flux 
in january the pentagon incorporated the brilliant pebbles 
concept into phase 1 that technology involves several thousand 
interceptors that would orbit the earth to seek and destroy a 
target by smashing into it at high speeds 
