<TEXT>
half a million homeless victims of the 
iranian earthquake are threatened by food shortages and the frigid 
weather about to descend on northern iran 
the quake june 21 killed 40000 people and injured 60000 in 
gilan and zanjan provinces where temperatures sometimes drop to 
zero in winter 
housing the refugees before then is the governments main 
priority abdollah nouri the iranian interior minister said last 
week 
nouri said on iranian television a parliamentary committee 
estimated more than 200000 houses would have to be built 
eventually then added in about two months we have to provide 
temporary shelters for the homeless 
relief efforts clearly have been inadequate the government 
already burdened by reconstruction needs after an eightyear war 
with iraq is short of cash equipment and materials 
the interior minister acknowledged that we cannot build what 
we want given the means at our disposal 
each homeless family will be given a limited amount of 
construction materials and technical support to build a shelter of 
about 10by13 feet to get through the winter nouri said 
he emphasized that the refugees would have to build the shelters 
themselves more than 100000 people now live in tents 
an asian diplomat based in tehran who visited the stricken 
areas to deliver truckloads of aid sent by his government told the 
associated press construction of the shelters had not yet begun 
he said reconstruction was in a bureaucratic tangle and it 
appeared doubtful that enough shelters could be built before 
winter he spoke on condition of anonymity 
tehran radio said construction of the shelters and repair of 
damaged houses involved five different ministries 
heavy winter snows and frigid temperatures are the rule in gilan 
and zanjan provinces 
manjil a gilan town in one of the worsthit areas is so windy 
that residents customarily spend winters in nearhibernation to 
escape the cold 
at a recent prayer meeting in rudbar a devastated town in gilan 
province friday prayer leader hojatoleslam vahedi urged 
authorities to rush construction of temporary housing 
the earthquake struck a rich agricultural area in midharvest 
survivors worry about facing winter with their crops ungathered and 
food scarce relief workers have been helping with the harvest 
vaccinating cattle and rebuilding irrigation canals 
a report on tehran radio said farmers would be paid higher 
prices for their crops this year 
nouri said on television that rebuilding schools before the new 
academic year starts in september was another priority he urged 
people to provide what help they could in rebuilding or repairing 
about 1200 structures 
more than 400 aftershocks some of them strong shook the two 
provinces after the june 21 quake the most recent was recorded 
july 19 
the tremors have caused panic among survivors and made it 
difficult for them to patch their damaged homes 
president hashemi rafsanjani toured the area after the quake and 
said all the people are anxious they cannot live in the damaged 
houses as they rightly cannot feel safe there 
tehran radio said power and water had been restored to the main 
towns in the quake area roads were being repaired and crews were 
working to restore services to 1500 affected villages 
parliament revised the current budget to allocate 300 million 
for the victims 
