night for a highly partisan democratic bill that even many of its 
supporters acknowledged privately stands no chance of becoming law 
president bush has vowed to veto any bill that imposes absolute 
spending ceilings on congressional candidates as both the house 
and senate versions do and that doesnt curb labor and business 
pacs rapidly escalating role in politics 
democrats in the senate bowed to bushs call to ban special 
interest political action committees entirely even though lawmakers 
in both parties acknowledge that the supreme court is likely to 
rule it an unconstitutional prohibition on free speech 
house democrats sought only to curb what they called fat cat 
corporate executive pacs cutting the amount they can contribute to 
each candidate for combined primary and november election campaigns 
to 2000 while leaving the current lid of 10000 on such gifts 
for union pacs 
