<TEXT>
the european community on saturday imposed an 
embargo on oil imports from iraq and kuwait as part of a series of 
tough sanctions aimed at striking at the heart of iraqi 
economic and military interests 
the action described as the strongest punitive measures ever 
taken by the the 12nation ec was aimed at forcing iraq to 
immediately unconditionally withdraw its invading forces from 
neighboring kuwait 
we will not be satisfied until there is not a single iraqi 
soldier in kuwait and until there is a legitimate and sovereign 
government in kuwait a spokesman for the italian foreign 
ministry giovanni castellaneta said 
the measures were announced after a threehour meeting of senior 
ec foreign ministry officials italy which holds the rotating ec 
presidency convened the emergency meeting to forge a joint 
response to the iraqi invasion thursday 
in addition to the oil embargo the 12 nations agreed to freeze 
iraqi assets halt arms sales to iraq and suspend all cooperation 
with baghdad in the military technical and scientific fields they 
also decided to suspend iraqs trade preference status 
the europeans are also seeking to protect kuwaiti assets in 
their countries and deny iraq financial benefit from its military 
action which the officials condemned as a brutal invasion 
several of the ec nations whose members include france west 
germany italy luxembourg belgium netherlands denmark greece 
ireland portugal spain and the united kingdom had earlier 
announced separate moves to freeze kuwaiti assets and halt arms 
sales to iraq 
the most punishing sanction is the embargo on iraqi and kuwaiti 
oil 
last year oil from the two countries accounted for 109 percent 
of the ecs total oil imports at the same time iraq is almost 
totally dependent on oil for its export earnings 
this will strike at the heart of iraq castellaneta said 
the oil embargo was formally proposed by france but the italian 
official said all other countries were in unanimous agreement the 
embargo could hurt some of the ec members such as denmark which 
depends on iraq and kuwait for more than 50 percent of its oil 
italian officials called the sanctions the toughest taken 
against iraq by any countries other than the united states and said 
they hoped other nations and organizations would follow suit 
especially the un security council 
the united states has also imposed an embargo on iraqi oil 
included in a decree issued thursday that blocked all imports from 
iraq and froze kuwaiti and iraqi assets in the united states iraqi 
oil had represented 75 percent of us oil imports according to 
the lastest industry figures this year 
ferdinando nelli the italian official in charge of european 
political affairs said the oil embargo marked without a doubt 
the strongest economic sanctions ever imposed by the ec 
he described the sanctions as a neartotal commercial embargo on 
iraq 
the strength of the measures and unanimity were in marked 
contrast to past crises when the ec members have been divided over 
whether to impose sanctions and how strong they should be 
during the us hostagetaking in iran for example trade 
sanctions imposed by the ec fell short of us expectations there 
have also been differences among the member nations on policy 
toward libya 
italian officials said the ec members did not discuss the 
possibility of joint military intervention in the persian gulf 
saying such a step would be taken only in concert with the united 
nations 
the 12 did not cut diplomatic relations or withdraw their 
ambassadors from iraq because that would make it impractical to 
defend their citizens in the area castellaneta said 
in a written statement the countries described as groundless 
and unacceptable iraqs justification for the military action 
iraq claimed it invaded after rebels overthrew kuwaits government 
the ec nations said they would do everthing they could to avoid 
an implicit recognition of the socalled provisional government 
iraq installed in kuwait 
the statement said the ec was ready to take part in any effort 
to defuse the crisis and was in close contact with several arab 
governments 
castellaneta said italian foreign minister gianni de michelis 
had received a message from secretary of state james a baker iii 
explaining the american position on the gulf crisis 
the spokesman said italy and the united states have identical 
viewpoints on the need for strong measures to force an iraqi 
withdrawal 
</TEXT>
