<TEXT>
dna testing a way to identify people or 
parentage using the bodys genetic code is reliable courtroom 
evidence but national standards for the tests are needed the 
office of technology assessment said saturday 
the ota which evaluates technical subjects for the congress 
said that dna testing first was introduced into the courtroom in 
1986 and already has been used in more than 2000 criminal 
investigations in 49 states and presented as evidence in more than 
185 court cases 
law enforcement agencies particularly the fbi want to 
establish a data bank of dna markers similar to the national files 
of fingerprints to help in the investigation of crimes but the 
ota said that such files could pose a threat to basic civil 
liberties 
in a report the ota said that the principles of dna 
identification are solid and that forensic uses of dna tests 
are both reliable and valid when properly performed and analyzed by 
skilled personnel 
evidence from dna patterns have been used to convict murders 
rapists and other criminals it also has been used to determine 
parentage and to identify bodies innocent men have been freed by 
dna testing and police have used the technology to guide their 
evaluation of suspects 
validity of dna testing has become so widely accepted the ota 
said that no state court has found that dna testing per se fails 
to meet established tests for admissibility although some courts 
have limited or barred its use in specific cases 
dna shorthand for deoxyribonucleic acid is the protein 
molecule that contains the genetic pattern for each individual 
except for red blood cells dna is present in every cell of the 
body every human has a unique dna pattern with the exception of 
identical twins who share the same genetic structure 
thus police who recover bodily fluids or tissue from a crime 
scene can use dna from those specimens to connect suspects with the 
crime 
dna patterns can be extracted from recovered specimens of blood 
semen body tissue bone hair roots saliva urine or the pulp of 
a tooth these patterns can then be compared to patterns found in 
blood or other specimens taken from the suspects 
the ota said the major difficulty with dna identification is the 
assurance that uniform standards are followed in conducting the 
tricky laboratory procedures in conducting the tests 
instituting quality assurance mechanisms should proceed 
without delay the ota said it called for a standardization that 
would assure that tests are conducted and interpreted the same way 
in each jurisdiction 
widespread use of dna testing the report said could be a 
significant weapon in fighting crime 
dna testing can save law enforcement and courts time and money 
by exonerating innocent suspects before trial or through plea 
bargaining for guilty parties as increasingly defendants are 
confronted with dna typing results the study said 
the ota said that society should prepare for the use of computer 
data banks for the storage of dna identification tests it said 
that 16 states and one county already have authorized or considered 
creating dna files for known offenders and the fbi is developing a 
system to store dna profiles for investigative uses 
centralized or linked databases containing dna profiles would 
permit rapid electronic comparison of results from tests on 
different samples within a laboratory and among laboratories 
nationwide the report said 
dna files kept of convicted offenders for instance could be 
used to analyze whether evidence found at a crime scene matched a 
profile in the database and thus provide police with a lead toward 
identifying a suspect the report said 
the report said that computer files of convicted offenders would 
be particularly helpful in investigating rape cases since released 
rapists are 105 times more likely than other offenders to be 
rearrested for rape the files also would aid police in 
investigating serial crimes because it would enable them to link 
individual cases more quickly 
creating such a computer data however the ota predicted will 
evoke several concerns about privacy 
because dna is specific to an individual and so highly 
personal some are reluctant to see any dna test results become 
part of a de facto national database it said 
many states now are hiring private laboratories to conduct dna 
testing and to provide expert witnesses when the evidence is used 
in court the ota said there were three major companies providing 
the service cellmark forensic science associates and lifecodes 
pricing systems vary with costs ranging from 325 per test to 
1500 for a case cost of expert witnesses range from 100 an hour 
to 1000 a day the report said 
the report said that congress could play a role in the 
development of dna testing by establishing standards and funding 
laboratories or training for personnel but the ota said congress 
also will have to consider whether to establish national computer 
databanks of dna information and wrestle with the concerns about 
privacy and civil rights in collecting and storing dna profiles 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

