<TEXT>
the red cross the nations biggest charity 
often takes days to respond to disasters has conflicts with other 
relief organizations and overstates its accomplishments according 
to a newspaper report 
a ninemonth investigation by the pittsburgh press that examined 
emergency responses to more than 200 disasters including every 
major one in the past five years showed that in some cases the 
red cross lived up to its promise to deliver help quickly fairly 
and compassionately 
but in others the review showed there were widespread 
deficiencies the alleged problems included delays of up to six 
days after a disaster hits before adequate numbers of trained 
workers arrive a lack of cooperation with local agencies and an 
emphasis on staging news media events during disasters 
the paper in a series set to begin in sundays newspaper also 
said the charity does not always spend all money donated for a 
specific disaster on that disaster 
the red cross said it was unfairly criticized because of highly 
publicized shortcomings last year following hurricane hugo and the 
northern california earthquake 
its absurd to look at last falls hurricane and earthquake 
and say the red cross cant do the job the red cross may have had 
a few little problems but we were dealing with two unprecedented 
disasters said barbara lohman a national red cross spokeswoman 
in washington dc 
if you want to be fair and get an accurate picture look at 
the hundreds of other disasters that we worked on and youll find 
that the red cross performance was almost flawless she told the 
newspaper 
the red cross unique operating position was created in 1900 
when congress passed a law making it the only volunteer agency 
required to aid victims of disaster 
today funded almost totally by donations from the american 
public the 12 billion operation promises immediate response to a 
disaster with food and shelter medical care clothing temporary 
housing and other basic needs 
to raise money it is red cross policy to stress image even in 
the early hours of a disaster according to the newspaper report 
two of the four names posted on the nightly callout roster at 
national headquarters in washington dc those people to be 
notified in case of a major disaster are fundraisers 
we had a film crew and a still photographer on the ground on 
the coast before hurricane hugo hit the mainland and with the 
earthquake we had a video crew in san francisco within the first 
24 hours ms lohman acknowledged 
most of the national disaster staff did not arrive until several 
days later 
the emphasis on fund raising irks many critics of the 
organization founded by civil war nurse clara barton in 1881 
when the fundraising ability of a disaster diminishes so 
does the national red cross said carl bradford west virginias 
director of emergency management the national organization is 
clearly driven by how much money it can raise so when the 
television crews and reporters leave the red cross is in the next 
cars out of town 
mayor anita wiley of shadyside ohio where 26 people were 
killed in flooding in midjune said the red cross didnt arrive 
for three days and then all they care about is raising money and 
their public image 
george moody chairman of american national red cross conceded 
that problems sometimes occur but he said theyre rare 
when you have 2200 active chapters involved in delivering 
services youre going to have inconsistency once in a while he 
said 
allegations of diverting funds designated for a specific 
disaster area surfaced after the northern california earthquake 
san francisco mayor art agnos charged the red cross was leaving 
town with 55 million contributed specifically for earthquake 
relief the red cross announced a month later it would spend 40 
million in additional earthquake relief 
while the red cross is by far the nations largest recipient of 
disaster contributions totaling 175 million last year the press 
concluded that less publicized disaster relief groups primarily 
the salvation army and other national church groups usually arrive 
first stay longer and do more 
</TEXT>
