<TEXT>
the stakes were high but both sides in 
the abortion debate refrained from public protests during a federal 
hearing on a challegnge to pennsylvanias strict abortion law 
three days of testimony ending last thursday took place in an 
atmosphere of restrained decorum the courtroom in reading with 
seating for about 15 was only occasionally filled 
the closest it came to high drama was when senior us district 
judge daniel h huyett admonished a witness for being evasive 
but belying the hearings mannerly discourses the 
specialinterest groups were hard at work 
seated beside senior deputy attorney general kate l mershimer 
throughout the trial was maura quinlan a harrisburg attorney whose 
law firm lists the pennsylvania catholic conference among its 
clients 
on the other side the suit filed on behalf of a group of 
abortion clinics and doctors was being handled in part by kathryn 
kolbert an attorney for the american civil liberties union 
attorneys for the clinics also received legal aid from planned 
parenthood in new york 
the suit challenges the laws provisions mandating a 24hour 
waiting period and that women notify their spouses in most cases 
before they have an abortion 
other contested sections require minors to get the permission of 
one parent or a court order before having an abortion and require 
clinics to file detailed reports with the state on each abortion 
huyett is not expected to rule for about a month the judge has 
blocked the disputed sections of the law pending a decision 
an appeal is likely regardless of the outcome 
pennsylvanias law is the most stringent of any state a tougher 
one was passed last month by the louisiana legislature but it was 
vetoed by gov buddy roemer only guam a us territory in the 
pacific has adopted stricter controls 
mershimers witnesses characterized the law as a reasonable set 
of guidelines that would protect the interests of women and 
families 
but attorneys for the clinics argued that the law set up 
draconian requirements that would set up a series of difficult 
hurdles for women seeking abortions 
the case has been closely monitored by abortion activists 
because it poses a potential of spawning a case that could lead to 
a us supreme court decision overturning roe vs wade the 1973 
ruling that established abortion as a constitutional right 
still advocates on both sides said they decided not to protest 
because it wouldnt serve a useful purpose 
planned parenthood spokeswoman suzanne mayer said abortion 
rights advocates were informally discouraged from protesting during 
a meeting last month of pennsylvanians for choice 
huyett is very fair theres no need to annoy him with 
protests she said if its in the courts youre going to 
leave it to the courts 
garnett biviano president of the pennsylvania prolife 
federation said protests are appropriately aimed at the 
legislature where the law was drafted 
we recognize the difference between the legislative branch and 
the judicial branch of government she said 
during closing arguments huyett gave some clues that he might 
have concerns with the law he previously has upheld challenges to 
pennsylvanias 1982 abortion law much of which was later struck 
down by the supreme court parts of that law were redrafted into 
the existing statute 
huyett said there may be a problem with the defining which 
medical emergencies would permit doctors to perform immediate 
abortions to avoid substantial injury to the mother 
on the 24hour waiting period huyett citing testimony 
speculated that the requirement might create a delay of several 
days or a week for some women and at certain times of pregnancy 
that wait could be medically significant 
