<TEXT>
the senate on saturday approved an 
intelligence budget for 1991 that eliminates us support for a 
covert war in cambodia and sharply restricts money for rebels in 
afghanistan according to sources 
the legislation passed by voice vote in the early morning 
hours authorizes us intelligence activities around the world 
from spy satellites to secret operations 
while most of the bill is secret it is believed to authorize 
spending in the neighborhood of 30 billion most of it is hidden 
away in the defense departments budget 
when the senate intelligence committee approved the measure on 
june 28 it eliminated a 13 million program of covert aid to a 
rebel coalition fighting cambodias communist government sources 
said 
the move was prompted by congressional fears that the aid was 
primarily helping the ruthless khmer rouge which is fighting 
alongside ussponsored rebel groups 
soon after the committee action president bush announced a 
series of policy changes in cambodia reflecting similar concerns 
the khmer rouge was responsible for the deaths of more than 1 
million cambodians during its 3year reign in the late 1970s it 
was chased from power when neighboring vietnam invaded 
reflecting a growing distaste on capitol hill for proxy 
conflicts in the third world the committee also slashed 100 
million from the 300 million request by the administration for aid 
to the mujahadeen rebels of afghanistan who are battling the 
sovietsponsored government in kabul 
washington and moscow have been trying to engineer an accord to 
end the conflict 
the bill governs the budgets of the central intelligence agency 
the national security agency which electronically spies on the 
world and defense intelligence agency 
it also provides for operations of the supersecret national 
reconnaissance office which is building and launching a new 
generation of spy satellites 
the house intelligence committee has deferred action on its 
version of the bill until congress returns in september hoping 
that by then policy decisions will have been made resolving 
disagreements on whether to fund conflicts like those in cambodia 
afghanistan and angola 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

