<TEXT>
andrew youngs hopes to become georgias first 
black governor have been reduced to a long shot as the former 
atlanta mayor tries to land a punch against lt gov zell miller 
the white frontrunner 
the democratic primary runoff in georgia headlines elections 
tuesday in four states including a strong challenge to kansas gov 
mike hayden in a republican primary voters in michigan and 
missouri also will go to the polls 
young came out swinging shortly after his secondplace finish in 
georgias july 17 primary in which he suffered a 
weakerthanexpected showing among black voters 
young charged that miller who is chairman of a small bank 
helped himself and key supporters by pushing banking laws through 
the legislature 
if it doesnt embarrass his supporters that he passed a tax 
bill and ended up with a bank i dont know what would embarrass 
them young said during a campaign stop in dekalb county 
saturday he added that he and miller just live by a different 
standard if id done that id have been in jail 
in the only negative advertising of the campaign a young 
television spot featured a miller cutout bouncing across the screen 
while an announcer accused him of changing positions on taxes and 
abortion 
on saturday miller soaked up the cheers of a crowd of 20000 as 
grand marshal of the georgia mountain fair parade in hiawassee and 
criticized young for mounting a negative campaign the andy young 
i used to know would not engage in that type of mudslinging 
miller said 
two polls released last week showed miller favored by more than 
50 percent of likely democratic voters and young trailing by 
margins of from 17 to 20 percent 
race has been little discussed in the runoff race and voter 
attention seems centered on millers proposal to legalize a state 
lottery 
young says he favors a referendum on a lottery but miller says 
young lacks the conviction to see it through both favor no new 
restrictions on abortion and say they dont expect to need to raise 
taxes 
miller captured 412 percent of the vote against four 
challengers in the primary last month young placed second with 
288 percent securing a majority of the black vote but not with 
the same strength that jesse jackson showed during his 1988 
presidential bid 
georgia law requires a candidate to win a majority of the vote 
to avoid a runoff the winner of tuesdays democratic runoff will 
face gop state rep johnny isakson who easily won a fourman 
primary race 
in recent weeks young has increased his efforts to woo the 
black vote an aspect of the campaign that critics said he had 
been neglecting 
miller meanwhile chided young for negative advertising and 
continued pushing the lottery he also summoned news reporters and 
camera crews to scenic locales a mountain stream a racecar 
drivers shop a high school science lab to record his thoughts 
on issues 
the signs point to a disintegrating young campaign said atlanta 
pollster claibourne darden 
its impossible for andy to win at this point one of the 
sure signs of a crumbling campaign is for the politician to openly 
and consistently cultivate his pocket vote the vote he should 
have in his pocket darden said 
state rep calvin smyre who is black said youngs problems 
among blacks stem from the perception that he left his base and 
pitched his campaign toward whites 
blacks make up about 28 percent of the states registered 
voters some critics contend that youngs effort to broaden his 
base by wooing urban suburban and rural whites during the primary 
campaign left black voters and black elected officials feeling 
ignored 
also working against young smyre said was that zell miller 
has not had a bad record when it comes to issues which relate to 
the black community and hes worked very well with black elected 
officials 
darden said youngs failure to score with more than about 15 
percent of the states white democratic voters showed he failed to 
erase the liberal image he developed in public life 
andy had the blueprint handed to him from the successful 
campaign last year of virginia gov l douglas wilder and andy 
refused to go with it and take a walk down the middle darden 
said 
in kansas hayden faces a strong challenge in the gop 
gubernatorial primary from a political newcomer challenger nestor 
weigand a wichita real estate executive has capitalized on 
widespread increases in property taxes as a strong issue against 
hayden 
former gov john carlin appears to be well ahead of his two 
opponents joan finney the state treasurer and topeka preacher 
fred phelps in seeking the democratic nomination for governor 
gop sen nancy kassebaum faces only token opposition in the 
primary 
in michigan us rep bill schuette is favored over attorney 
clark durant to win the gop senate nomination the winner will take 
on democratic sen carl levin in november 
michigans democratic gov james blanchard has no primary 
opposition his opponent in november is expected to be state senate 
republican leader john engler who has only token opposition in the 
primary 
missouri has no governor or senate race this year 
