<TEXT>
south korea and the soviet union once 
bitter enemies have agreed to broad economic cooperation as a step 
toward formal diplomatic ties newspapers reported saturday 
the agreement was made at two days of governmentlevel talks 
that ended in moscow on friday the newspapers in seoul said in 
reports from moscow 
the talks were arranged after soviet leader mikhail s gorbachev 
sent a letter to president roh taewoo last month calling for joint 
efforts to help promote economic and other relations between the 
two countries 
the two leaders met in san francisco in early june in the first 
encounter of top leaders of the two countries which do not 
recognize one another the soviet union is a close ally and arms 
provider for seouls rival communist north korea 
both sides agreed to continue the negotiations in seoul next 
month the newspapers said 
seoul newspapers quoting korean delegates in moscow said the 
moscow talks laid a solid foundation for an early normalization of 
relations between the two countries 
during the twoday talks both sides presented details of 
projects or cooperation they want to promote in 11 sectors 
including fishery forestry electronics aviation steel and 
metals natural gas and petrochemicals the newspapers said 
the soviet union also presented a list of consumer goods it 
wants from south korea the newspapers said 
south korean delegates said in seoul before departing that they 
would offer to help ease an acute shortage of consumer goods in the 
soviet union such as soap shoes toothpaste radio and television 
sets and other electronic items 
government sources who spoke on condition of anonymity 
indicated that south korea may provide loans for the soviet union 
to import korean consumer goods 
despite the lack of diplomatic relations seoul and moscow have 
greatly strengthened economic and other nonpolitical links in 
recent years especially after the 1988 olympics in seoul 
establishing formal ties with the soviet union is a prime goal 
of south koreas policy of improving ties with socialist and 
communist nations seoul officials believe such ties would help 
open north koreas closed society and thus ease tension on the 
korean peninsula 
