the bush administration lifted its objections 
to legislation creating a commission to probe the savings and loan 
collapse after being assured the panel would not interfere with 
criminal prosecutions senate sponsors of the bill said saturday 
sens christopher bond rmo and christopher dodd dconn 
released letters from the departments of justice and treasury 
indicating the administration dropped its objections to a 
senatesponsored bill setting up an eightmember bipartisan 
investigative commission 
administration officials had said they would fight a rival 
version of the legislation the banking law enforcement act of 
1990 passed by the house on july 31 and had spoken out against a 
proposal by the national governors association last week for such 
an investigative panel 
in a letter to sens bond and dodd made public saturday deputy 
assistant attorney general bruce navarro restated administration 
concerns that the house version of the legislation could pose 
real dangers to ongoing savingsandloan criminal investigations 
we are particularly pleased that unlike the house bill your 
proposal takes care to ensure that ongoing criminal investigations 
and prosecutions conducted by the department are neither 
compromised nor impeded 
the executive and legislative branches of government 
historically have feuded over companion investigations of various 
scandals by the justice department and congressional committees 
this was dramatized recently in a federal appellate courts 
decision reversing one of former marine lt col oliver norths 
irancontra convictions and ordering a lower court to review other 
convictions to determine whether immunized testimony north gave the 
congress was impermissibly used against him by irancontra 
prosecutors 
bond and dodd got the administration to lift its objections to 
their sampl factfinding commission by agreeing to amend the 
legislation under the new version the commission would be 
required to inform the justice department when it plans to call 
witnesses implicated in savings and loan failures 
the two senators said in a statement saturday that if the 
department or the resolution trust corporation certifies that 
commission testimony could jeopardize a pending criminal 
investigation the commission would not call the witnesses 
however the commission has the authority to request 
additional powers after 60 days if it believes the investigation is 
impaired in any way their statement said 
in his letter navarro said we have concluded that your 
proposal constitutes a workable compromise solution that adequately 
takes into account the legitimate concerns of all involved 
consequently we have no objection to its enactment 
bryce harlow an assistant treasury secretary in charge of 
legislative affairs said in a separate letter that his department 
is satisfied the senate proposal has sufficient safeguards to 
protect ongoing civil and criminal investigations 
a host of congressional committees already is conducting various 
