the navy investigating allegations of cheating 
on nuclear reactor safety inspections aboard the uss nimitz has 
restricted four crew members aboard ship 
no charges have been filed navy spokesman lt donald thomas 
said this action is a standard precautionary measure taken to 
ensure the presence of individuals until an investigation is 
complete 
four nimitz sailors approached local news media last week and 
said sailors aboard the nimitz were cheating on inspections and 
were overworked and insufficiently trained to react to a nuclear 
accident 
it wasnt known if the four restricted sailors were the same 
ones who had approached the news media 
the nimitz is completing a monthlong maintenance run at the 
puget sound naval shipyard in bremerton 
thomas comment came in written response to questions submitted 
by kirotv 
the station aired a segment thursday night in which the sailors 
alleged crew members had cheated on reactor inspections that some 
nuclear operators had to work up to 100 hours a week in port and 
that many crew were not trained sufficiently to react to a nuclear 
accident 
the crew members whose faces and voices were masked also 
alleged that some had considered disabling the reactor to ease 
their heavy work schedule 
one of the sailors later told the associated press that the 
comment was not meant as a direct threat but that overworked crew 
members might resort to minor acts of sabotage to put their 
commanding officers in a bad light 
