<TEXT>
senate and house negotiators on clean air 
legislation reached agreement friday on a schedule for ending by 
the close of the decade use of chemicals that damage the ozone 
layer but leaders acknowledged the most difficult issues of the 
legislation have yet to be discussed 
among other provisions the negotiators agreed to forbid states 
and local governments from restricting or banning the chemicals for 
two years 
the conference committee is not scheduled to meet again until 
after the august congressional recess house and senate staffers 
were directed to work through the month to draft possible 
compromises on various parts of the two bills 
we dont have much time ahead of us said sen max baucus 
dmont the conference chairman noting there are only 23 
legislative days remaining until congress is scheduled to adjourn 
in early october 
negotiators said they hoped the agreement on ozonedestroying 
chemicals would help break the deadlock 
that agreement calls for phasing out such chemicals including 
chlorofluorocarbons halons and carbon tetrachloride widely used 
as coolants solvents and foam blowing agents by the end of the 
decade 
some substitute chemicals that are less harmful to the 
environment such as hcfcs chlorofluorocarbons that contain one or 
more hydrogen atoms would be phased out over the next 40 years 
the measure also calls for recylcing of these chemicals by 1992 
and the installation of precautions to prevent routine release into 
the air 
the ban on local action will affect at least 17 states and 
communities that have acted on their own in various ways to 
restrict the use of ozonedepleting chemicals 
the compromise substantially mirrors requirements in the 
montreal protocol the international treaty on ozonedepleting 
chemicals 
the house and senate conferees have been struggling for nearly a 
month in an attempt to reconcile different bills approved by the 
house and senate that would impose tougher air pollution controls 
on automobiles industry and electric utilities 
but so far the two sides have not even discussed specific 
compromises on the most controversial areas of the bills including 
what smogreducing controls to impose on automobiles and how 
industry must cut toxic chemical emissions 
at fridays session the house and senate members had trouble 
even agreeing what issues staff members should discuss during the 
august recess 
the ozone layer 25 miles or so above the earth protects living 
organisms from the harmful ultraviolet rays of the sun which can 
cause skin cancer the normally inert chemicals in question last so 
long in the atmosphere that they eventually rise to to ozone layer 
where ultraviolet light breaks them down and liberates chlorine 
that destroys ozone 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

